WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.540
dobbiamo difendere, quello in cui noi come sindacato possiamo fare molto, quello in cui

00:05.500 --> 00:12.400
possiamo agire molto e anche questo, da questa prospettiva di pace. Io penso che come soggetto

00:12.400 --> 00:16.860
che parla, incide e pesa sulla scena internazionale il contributo dell'Europa che vogliamo può

00:16.860 --> 00:20.880
anche essere questo e questo nella chiesa internazionale aperta è moltissimo e l'orizzonte

00:20.880 --> 00:22.160
io penso sia questo.

00:26.400 --> 00:32.060
Bene, io ringrazio i nostri tre interlocutori per i loro interventi densi, impegnativi,

00:32.800 --> 00:39.820
belli per questa discussione. Noi ci rivediamo alle 14.30 per facilitare le vostre esigenze

00:39.820 --> 00:44.520
materiali c'è un buffet al piano di sotto al quale si può accedere.

01:05.280 --> 01:07.400
Allora ricominciamo.

01:28.140 --> 01:35.080
Dopo i contributi di questa mattina molto interessanti per il loro alto profilo, ora

01:35.080 --> 01:40.020
i lavori del pomeriggio continuano entrando con uno sguardo più specifico nel settore

01:40.020 --> 01:48.780
dei saperi e delle conoscenze sulle tracce dei percorsi di tre occasioni. A Bologna

01:48.780 --> 01:54.060
nel 1998 è stata firmata una dichiarazione da parte dei ministri dell'istruzione di

01:54.060 --> 02:00.900
quattro paesi europei, Italia, Gran Bretagna, Francia e Germania. Questa dichiarazione in

02:00.900 --> 02:07.160
seguito poi sottoscritta da altri quaranta paesi dell'Unione Europea aveva lo scopo

02:07.160 --> 02:13.100
di unificare, ha lo scopo di unificare i sistemi universitari, finalizzata a definire un'area

02:13.100 --> 02:19.280
europea dell'istruzione superiore. Il secondo percorso di cui seguiamo le tracce

02:19.280 --> 02:24.440
con le relazioni del pomeriggio è quello della Carta di Lisbona. Nel 2000, come tutti

02:24.440 --> 02:32.840
sapete, i governi membri dell'Unione Europea hanno sottoscritto questa carta per finalizzare

02:32.840 --> 02:41.520
la maggiore competitività dell'Unione Europea a un percorso fatto di miglioramento della

02:42.200 --> 02:49.180
società della conoscenza. Infine, il terzo percorso, che è quello di Copenhagen, in

02:49.180 --> 02:55.640
cui il Consiglio dei Ministri dell'Unione Europea ha sottoscritto una dichiarazione

02:55.640 --> 03:02.520
sull'istruzione e formazione professionale, ha finalizzato a raggiungere l'unificazione

03:02.520 --> 03:09.680
dei titoli di qualifica dell'istruzione e della formazione professionale. Oggi abbiamo

03:09.680 --> 03:16.900
le persone che voi vedete nelle relazioni pomeridiane e avremmo dovuto cominciare con

03:16.900 --> 03:24.540
Martin Romer, che è il segretario dell'EQC, se l'ho pronunciato bene, EQC, che è il

03:24.540 --> 03:29.560
Comitato dei Sindacati della Scuola dei Paesi membri e fa parte anche dell'Internazionale

03:29.560 --> 03:36.560
dell'Educazione. Però il professore Paul Benet, che è coordinatore dell'EQC, ha un

03:36.560 --> 03:40.960
uomo che parte alle quattro e mezza, anzi un treno, e quindi cediamo a lui la parola

03:40.960 --> 03:46.780
per primo e in seguito parlerà il segretario dell'EQC, che è Martin Romer, alla mia destra.

03:46.900 --> 03:50.740
Ora do la parola a Paul Benet, se non ho sbagliato, no, ho fatto il contrario, do la parola a

03:50.740 --> 03:52.960
Paul Benet per la sua relazione.

04:06.560 --> 04:11.860
Due scopi, prima di tutto per non essere in grado di parlare italiano, vorrei scopiare per

04:11.860 --> 04:16.040
non essere in grado di parlare italiano, che significa che dovrete ascoltare la mia

04:16.040 --> 04:21.160
presentazione, purtroppo, in inglese, con un'interpretazione. Ho dato una copia del mio

04:21.160 --> 04:24.660
documento all'interpretero, quindi penso che saranno in grado di darvi una versione

04:24.660 --> 04:30.520
abbastanza accurata di cosa vorrei dirvi quest'oggi. L'altra scopia,

04:30.520 --> 04:37.140
che ho sentito molte volte che bisogna fare nel venire dall'Unione Kingdom a un evento

04:37.140 --> 04:42.340
in un altro paese europeo, e questo è, una volta di nuovo, dobbiamo sbagliare per la nostra

04:42.340 --> 04:47.180
attitudine dei governi, le attitudini dei governi dell'Unione Europea. La riferizione

04:47.180 --> 04:54.120
è stata fatta quest'oggi per la sua attitudine a Mr. Bush e la situazione in Iraq, che è

04:54.120 --> 04:58.500
anche qualcosa che mi dispiace profondamente, e la mia Unione mi dispiace profondamente, ma

04:58.500 --> 05:05.240
sicuramente, come vedete dalla mia presentazione, ci sono problemi riguardo i problemi continui

05:05.240 --> 05:10.360
con l'Unione Kingdom e il progetto europeo, che, penso, vengono al centro di alcune delle

05:10.360 --> 05:17.060
cose che avete parlato quest'oggi. Sicuramente, ho guardato con estremità l'envio alla vostra

05:17.060 --> 05:22.760
discussione quest'oggi, perché so quante difficoltà sarebbe per una Unione Britannica

05:22.760 --> 05:30.180
e di avere una discussione più profonda e più profonda sui problemi riguardo al processo

05:30.180 --> 05:34.200
di gestire la Constituzione europea, come avete fatto quest'oggi. Quindi, guardo su questo

05:34.200 --> 05:37.760
con un'enorme apprezzamento, e sono molto felice di essere presente per vedere alcuni

05:37.760 --> 05:43.880
di questi problemi. Ora, andiamo al mio noto preparato, e, scusate-me, lo vorrò leggere

05:43.880 --> 05:51.020
e i interpretatori lo tradurranno. Grazie molto per invitarmi a parlare alla vostra

05:51.680 --> 05:55.840
discussione oggi. Sono un ufficiale nazionale di NACVI, l'Università e il Collegio Dettorale

05:55.840 --> 06:02.900
dell'Unione Kingdom. Nel livello europeo, sono il chair del Comitato di Estandere l'Educazione

06:02.900 --> 06:07.720
e del Piacere dell'Europa della regione europea del Piacere dell'Unione Globale e dell'Educazione

06:07.720 --> 06:14.040
Internazionale, e non, come sembra, il vostro programma da E.T.U.C.E. Nel livello internazionale,

06:14.360 --> 06:19.960
ero un membro dell'E.I. Global Task Force on Higher Education, che ha rapportato al World

06:19.960 --> 06:26.400
Congress in Porto Alegre, in giulio 2004. Mi raccomando questa opportunità di informare

06:26.400 --> 06:30.560
voi di sviluppamenti in l'educazione alta, a livello europeo e internazionale, che hanno

06:30.560 --> 06:36.560
avuto i colleghi di conoscenza in le Unioni Dettorale affiliate all'E.I. in recenti anni.

06:37.220 --> 06:41.960
Il lavoro europeo e internazionale dell'E.I. in l'educazione alta e la ricerca interloca

06:42.630 --> 06:47.060
e sono questi i problemi interloccati e le prospettive delle Unioni Dettorale sulle quali

06:47.060 --> 06:54.300
voglio parlare con voi oggi. Spero che la discussione vi stimola le vostre discussioni, ma

06:54.300 --> 07:03.400
anche che vi accorgi di partecipare nelle nostre discussioni al Comitato per l'Educazione

07:03.400 --> 07:09.920
e la ricerca dell'E.I. a livello europeo. Questo comitato rappresenta le Unioni

07:09.920 --> 07:15.080
Dettorale e la ricerca interloccate all'E.I. e ha iniziato l'E.I. a parlare autoritativamente

07:15.080 --> 07:20.500
per i lavoratori della nostra sectora durante il processo di Bologna e i ministri e i rectori

07:20.500 --> 07:26.080
delle Università non hanno sempre voluto ascoltare o entrare in un dialogo con noi. E questo

07:26.080 --> 07:32.140
è un problema che avrò a ritornare in questo papo. Per prima cosa, vi schizzo le origini e

07:32.140 --> 07:37.660
il background del processo di Bologna e dove è ora. E poi, potrebbe essere utile se

07:37.660 --> 07:42.280
voglio dire un po' dei temi che il debattimento di Bologna ha mostrato nel Kingdome Unito.

07:43.440 --> 07:46.320
Poi, vorrei parlare dei problemi currenti al livello europeo e, finalmente,

07:46.600 --> 07:50.560
parlare della relazione tra Bologna e i sviluppamenti in l'area globale.

07:52.440 --> 07:56.360
Il processo di Bologna inizia ad accompagnare la maggior parte dei sistemi per l'educazione

07:56.360 --> 08:01.660
alta dell'Europa. Inizia con la Declarazione de Sorbonne, che si ha scritto solo per l'Italia,

08:02.510 --> 08:10.830
e poi, in 1998, si è uscita con la Declarazione de Sorbonne, che si ha scritto per il 29 governamenti.

08:12.360 --> 08:17.800
Il numero di signatari continua a crescere, con 40 paesi a partire dalla conferenza

08:17.800 --> 08:23.160
di Berlina l'anno scorso, e, da allora, con la Mordova, che ha annunciato la sua intenzione

08:23.160 --> 08:29.480
di iscriverci in giugno, e l'Ucraina, in seguito, l'ultimo mese. Questa crescita

08:29.480 --> 08:35.480
simbolizza l'importanza del processo come un processo genuinamente pan-europeano.

08:36.540 --> 08:42.620
La Bologna è stata sviluppata e elaborata da 1999 con further conferenze interministeriali

08:42.620 --> 08:50.620
in Praga nel 2001, e in Berlina nel settembre 2003. Le preparazioni sono ora all'interno

08:50.620 --> 08:58.560
della prossima conferenza in Bergen, in Norvegi, nel maio 2005. Il processo è essenzialmente

08:59.660 --> 09:04.560
interministeriali e, da inizio, è andato fuori dalla Unione Europea e le sue strutture

09:04.560 --> 09:09.340
e è andato avanti molto più velocemente che i processi dell'Europa hanno inizialmente

09:09.340 --> 09:15.560
potuto fare, altrimenti l'Europa è diventata un importante giocatore e forza di guida

09:15.560 --> 09:20.780
per questo processo. Dunque, il processo è costruito sui trattamenti intergovernmentali

09:20.780 --> 09:25.940
e non sui trattamenti statuitivi, come è stato il caso nel sistema EU.

09:27.900 --> 09:33.120
Quali sono gli essenziali del processo? L'obiettivo è di creare un'area europeana

09:33.120 --> 09:38.780
per l'educazione alta dell'Europa nel 2010, per che i sistemi per l'educazione alta dell'Europa

09:38.780 --> 09:44.920
avessero convergito verso un livello sufficiente di comunità per raggiungere la mobilità interna

09:44.920 --> 09:49.120
e la mutuale riconoscenza, che sono stati obiettivi a lungo termine per l'Europa

09:49.120 --> 09:54.040
dentro le loro bordi e per presentare una faccia coerente per l'educazione alta dell'Europa

09:54.040 --> 09:58.760
all'interno del resto del mondo in modo da essere in grado di essere un giocatore effettivo

09:58.760 --> 10:05.000
nel mercato globale rapidamente sviluppato. La velocità con la quale il progresso è stato fatto

10:05.000 --> 10:10.080
verso questi obiettivi ambiziosi è meraviglioso, in particolare rispetto al progresso veloce

10:10.080 --> 10:15.840
che l'Europa ha fatto verso gli obiettivi simili ma più limitati negli ultimi 20 anni.

10:17.060 --> 10:22.080
Il corno di questo processo è la convergenza, attraverso il sviluppo di un patto comune dei corsi di degree

10:22.080 --> 10:30.360
basati su tre cicli limitati di tempo, definiti dal processo Bologna, i bachelors, i maestri e i degree drattuali.

10:32.720 --> 10:37.700
Il patto sembra superficially come il modello dell'Europa, ma in pratica le soluzioni adottate

10:37.700 --> 10:45.360
all'Europa possono essere più vicini al modello dell'Europa. Il movimento verso questo patto

10:45.360 --> 10:50.440
è stato pacciato, con alcuni paesi imposando i cicli di tre anni, due anni e cinque anni

10:50.440 --> 10:56.900
sopra i suoi existingi patti. Noto che in Italia il debattimento sul modello dei bachelors e dei maestri

10:56.900 --> 11:03.040
è recentemente riempito, solo tre anni dopo che è stato adottato.

11:03.920 --> 11:09.300
La confidenza nel processo e il mantenimento dei standard comuni saranno underpinati

11:09.300 --> 11:16.100
per le mesure di assurdo di qualità in cui il netto europeo per assurdo di qualità ha un ruolo importante

11:16.100 --> 11:24.040
e il sviluppo dei diploma rendendo il contenuto dei corsi più espliciti e più facilmente comparabili.

11:25.030 --> 11:29.940
Ora vorrei dire un po' dei trend che informano la discussione relativamente limitata

11:29.940 --> 11:36.580
su Bologna nel mio paese, l'Europa. A questo punto il governo dell'Europa è stato

11:36.580 --> 11:41.880
particolarmente complesso per Bologna, credendo evidentemente che i bachelors e i maestri

11:41.880 --> 11:47.040
si accorgono così vicino alla pratica dell'Europa che nessun cambiamento radicale è necessario,

11:47.040 --> 11:53.780
anche se questa complessità è lentamente erogata. Il governo dell'Europa ha la visione

11:53.780 --> 11:59.320
dell'UK come una bridge tra l'Europa e l'USA, ma in pratica la sua pensione si riempie

11:59.320 --> 12:03.660
verso i modelli dell'U.S. in molti rispetto. Questa è una tendenza che è possibile

12:03.660 --> 12:09.160
di accelerare con l'enlargimento dell'Europa, che il governo dell'U.K. vede come un'incorruzione

12:09.600 --> 12:15.460
a una diffusione e un sforzo di un motivo comune dell'Europa. Questo è arrivato al momento

12:15.460 --> 12:20.440
in cui la prossima Constituzione dell'Europa è sotto discussione e in cui molte Unioni,

12:20.900 --> 12:25.300
certamente nell'U.K., vorranno vedere l'Europa essere più esplicita per il suo cover

12:25.300 --> 12:31.440
dell'educazione e dell'agenda sociale. Nel cuore dell'agenda blaire si trova

12:31.440 --> 12:37.820
una forte credenza nella virtù e nel valore della competizione. Nessun aspetto di vita pubblica

12:37.820 --> 12:41.160
dovrà essere risparmato da quello che vedono come i rigori e le disciplini della competizione.

12:41.160 --> 12:45.180
Il mercato potrà determinare tutti, e quindi l'argomento è che tutti saranno beneficiari.

12:47.400 --> 12:51.560
Questo si tratta di un'educazione e di un'incorruzione, le due prezioni del sector pubblico,

12:52.040 --> 12:56.780
che i protagonisti della competizione vogliono riposare dal sector pubblico e aprire

12:56.780 --> 13:01.780
al mercato. Da un punto di vista del corpo dell'America, questo non è difficile da capire.

13:02.020 --> 13:07.040
La competizione, in loro pensi, va da mano in mano con il profitto. E' molto più difficile

13:07.040 --> 13:12.480
da giustificare in termini delle caratteristiche di servizio pubblico valuti, che sono condizionate

13:12.480 --> 13:19.800
a un grado più o meno di grado attraverso l'Europa, e che la competizione, i valori commerciali

13:19.800 --> 13:27.100
e il profitto si affrontano. Controllo democratico, accontabilità pubblica, accessibilità,

13:27.280 --> 13:34.500
servizio alla società e capacità di prendere la vista a lungo termine, solo a pochi.

13:34.500 --> 13:39.420
Nel Reino Unito, il supostamente super efficiente sector privato, colpendo sotto il peso

13:39.420 --> 13:44.760
della competizione globale, è difficile sostenere l'argomento che il privato sia buono o

13:44.760 --> 13:50.660
anche efficiente. Eppure la vita pubblica nel Reino Unito si trova in mano di bossi corporei

13:50.660 --> 13:55.800
del sector privato, che devono portare nuove discipline e un nuovo focus ai servizi pubblici.

13:57.000 --> 14:01.940
Da l'incorruzione della prima Politecnica, come le nuove università, e delle further

14:01.940 --> 14:08.140
education colleges, in gli anni 1990, i corrispondenti di queste instituzioni sono stati

14:08.140 --> 14:12.360
attaccati con i direttori e i maneggi del sector privato, molti di cui non sa nulla o niente

14:12.360 --> 14:19.180
di l'educazione. La storia è simile ai board di ospedali. Un trend parallelo è l'appointamento

14:19.180 --> 14:25.940
dei maneggi e dei cittadini del sector privato, molti di cui hanno fatto una virtù del

14:25.940 --> 14:30.460
lack of experience of the service which they now manage, and they wish to treat courses

14:30.460 --> 14:37.180
and students as outputs or commodities. The pre-1992 universities, called in our system

14:37.180 --> 14:43.200
the old universities, have been spared the worst excesses of this shift. This is part

14:43.200 --> 14:51.990
of a wider trend, often towards spurious competition and actual whole or part privatisation of

14:51.990 --> 14:58.130
our public services. The education unions and the trade union movement in general have

14:58.130 --> 15:02.910
been the most sustained critics of the flawed concept of competition in public services,

15:03.050 --> 15:08.790
as basic as health and education, which many of us regard as a right, access to which should

15:08.790 --> 15:14.650
be determined by need, not individual wealth or the ability to pay. Equally, the unions

15:14.650 --> 15:21.930
assert that all deserve high quality public services, not the spurious choice based on

15:21.930 --> 15:28.270
which is central to the market philosophy. The rhetoric and the actions of the UK government,

15:28.570 --> 15:33.270
which seeks to apply the market model to higher education and to link it to the agenda of

15:33.270 --> 15:39.490
globalisation, ignores the deep rooted culture of internationalism and cooperation in higher

15:39.490 --> 15:47.230
education and research. That historic international collegial culture is present at institutional

15:47.230 --> 15:52.890
level, but perhaps even more powerfully in the organic relationships which develop between

15:52.890 --> 15:59.490
individuals and groups of scholars locally, nationally and globally. These relationships

15:59.490 --> 16:04.770
have evolved as circumstances change, for example to accommodate the demands of mass higher

16:04.770 --> 16:10.110
education and the dramatic transition resulting from the internet and the email revolution.

16:11.770 --> 16:15.430
Teachers and researchers have nothing to fear from this globalisation and an international

16:15.430 --> 16:21.070
frame of reference. This is the environment for their daily work, but the link of globalisation

16:21.070 --> 16:27.090
to the market place is pernicious and dangerous. The UK higher education unions, my own union

16:27.090 --> 16:32.350
NATPI and the association of university teachers have fought against this link, have fought

16:32.350 --> 16:38.150
ministerial complacency about the Bologna process, the threat of gaps and the supposed

16:38.150 --> 16:43.270
safeguards that are in place. And in the process we've built new alliances with NGOs

16:43.270 --> 16:50.090
and a new generation of activist networks. The Bologna debate on convergence of European

16:50.090 --> 16:54.910
higher education systems, which may be a good in itself, needs to take account of these

16:54.910 --> 16:59.850
global challenges. It's also important to explore the implications of Bologna and of

16:59.850 --> 17:06.650
globalisation for the university's historic role as society's key generators of research

17:06.650 --> 17:13.590
and critical enquiry. What are the practical effects of the competition model for the UK

17:13.590 --> 17:19.910
higher education system? Underlying a number of the policy imperatives is the UK government

17:19.910 --> 17:26.550
target for 50% of the generation leaving school to enter higher education, but with no commensurate

17:26.550 --> 17:33.810
increase in resources to achieve this goal. This will clearly have profound implications

17:33.810 --> 17:38.490
for the character of higher education and for the jobs and working conditions of our members.

17:40.050 --> 17:45.290
Some of the government's proposed solutions, most already being applied, are already having

17:45.290 --> 17:50.850
a detrimental effect on the sector and on our members. One of the principal new policies

17:50.850 --> 17:55.290
to achieve the student numbers target in the UK is to shift the concept of higher education

17:55.290 --> 18:00.230
and of the degree itself. Just as countries across Europe are struggling with the three

18:00.230 --> 18:06.490
time-limited cycles defined by the Bologna process, bachelors, masters and doctoral degrees,

18:06.990 --> 18:11.730
which for many countries across Europe mean a shortening of the length of study to a minimum

18:11.730 --> 18:17.470
of three years for bachelors and two years for masters degrees, the UK, which already

18:17.470 --> 18:23.830
had such a system in broad outline, is introducing even shorter two-year foundation degrees.

18:23.830 --> 18:31.030
For many subjects this will be a new label on an existing intermediate level vocational course.

18:31.830 --> 18:36.490
There will be some new courses which will be aimed at increasing access, and the value

18:36.490 --> 18:42.110
of many foundation courses will be judged by how readily they can be extended to a full

18:42.110 --> 18:48.170
degree by further study, although the government envisages that for many students two-year

18:48.170 --> 18:55.470
foundation degrees will be final qualifications. Many commentators fear that the government's

18:55.470 --> 18:59.950
proposed expansion of higher education will be achieved by a significant devaluing of

18:59.950 --> 19:05.270
the product, which is an offer to many young people. At the European level, inter-ministerial

19:05.270 --> 19:10.810
meetings in the Bologna process are watching this development with some scepticism. However,

19:11.150 --> 19:16.370
it's notable that a few other European countries, including the Czech Republic, are following

19:16.370 --> 19:23.550
the UK down the two-year route. Meanwhile at masters level, the UK model for masters

19:23.550 --> 19:29.630
degrees is based mainly on one-year programmes, in contrast to the Bologna prescription of

19:29.630 --> 19:35.070
two years, and this too could be a source of future conflict with our Bologna partners.

19:37.530 --> 19:43.850
The fear of potential devaluing of qualifications is justified by the government's expectation

19:43.850 --> 19:49.010
that an increasing proportion of higher education will be delivered in local intermediate

19:49.010 --> 19:53.730
colleges. As universities become more closely linked with colleges offering intermediate

19:53.730 --> 19:59.350
qualifications, we are likely to see a shift in the boundary between further education

19:59.350 --> 20:04.850
and higher education, and the development of networks of feeder institutions around

20:04.850 --> 20:11.090
major universities on lines closer to the US model. While this has potential advantages

20:11.090 --> 20:16.410
in extending access and in opening up new opportunities for our members who teach

20:16.410 --> 20:22.230
in colleges, there can be little doubt that in the government's view a lowering of the

20:22.230 --> 20:29.210
unit price per student is the key determinant. In the same spirit, the government is seeking

20:29.210 --> 20:39.470
to differentiate universities to create a hierarchy of institutions, elite institutions and

20:39.470 --> 20:43.050
universities, which are actively funded to do a full research programme, a governmental

20:43.050 --> 20:48.850
response to limited funds and burgeoning demand. It will be extremely hard, if not impossible,

20:49.290 --> 20:54.430
for other institutions to break into the Charmed Circle. The crucial link between teaching

20:54.430 --> 21:01.730
and research and scholarship will be broken. Many students will be taught in institutions

21:01.730 --> 21:09.270
where research is at best a marginal activity. It will mean a diminution of the opportunities

21:09.270 --> 21:15.750
many academics have to pursue their research interests, raising fundamental questions about

21:15.750 --> 21:21.150
the nature of the academic's role, and reducing the role of academic staff in a way which

21:21.150 --> 21:26.990
I suspect would be simply unacceptable in many European universities outside the UK.

21:27.850 --> 21:34.830
Already the hierarchy is ossifying into self-selected bands of institutions headed by the Russell

21:34.830 --> 21:41.250
Group of Universities, a would-be Ivy League, in the seat of most research funding. As well

21:41.250 --> 21:45.990
as simply calling for more research funding to match the levels recommended by the OECD,

21:46.190 --> 21:51.490
unions in the UK have called for more fluid responses. These could include encouraging

21:51.490 --> 21:57.470
departments and groups of staff to do research regardless of the institution they're in, fostering

21:57.470 --> 22:03.870
relations between institutions and the imaginative use of consortia. Also, while we attach great

22:03.870 --> 22:08.890
importance to the overriding principle of public sector funding and values, in practice

22:08.890 --> 22:14.330
diversity of funding sources is welcome, subject to appropriate protections.

22:15.650 --> 22:20.490
This brings me to another theme in the UK system which may be familiar to you in Italy.

22:20.490 --> 22:25.410
It's clear that the proportion of funding for higher education and research from the state

22:25.410 --> 22:31.570
is and will continue to shrink, and funding from non-public sources, including corporate

22:31.570 --> 22:37.450
finance, tuition fees and project funding, is expected to grow. One of the key planks

22:37.450 --> 22:44.090
of government policy in the UK, tuition fees paid by students, is one of the most divisive

22:44.090 --> 22:50.690
issues in UK politics today. The union's response, as well as unsuccessfully to oppose

22:50.690 --> 22:55.370
the fees policy, has been to argue for increased public investment in higher education and

22:55.370 --> 23:00.910
research, but also to seek to ensure that the terms on which private funding is deployed

23:00.910 --> 23:06.230
match the same high standards of public funding, particularly in terms of academic freedom,

23:06.850 --> 23:08.810
democratic governance and accountability.

23:10.730 --> 23:17.050
In the UK, institutions are also moving into increased reliance on short-term and part-time

23:17.050 --> 23:22.670
contracts for their staff, and to teaching only appointments. The increasing availability

23:22.670 --> 23:27.550
of postgraduate students without grants or other sources of income has opened up a new

23:27.550 --> 23:32.930
and cheap form of academic labour, as well as an employment group who unions find it

23:32.930 --> 23:38.410
difficult to recruit or to represent. Once again, these trends are clearly cost driven.

23:38.910 --> 23:43.770
They represent a challenge to academic freedom, employment rights and the quality of the education

23:43.770 --> 23:50.890
on offer. Quality is already taking on a new significance in institutions where students

23:50.890 --> 23:56.270
are customers with new rights and expectations, and with the power to challenge what they

23:56.270 --> 24:02.650
perceive as poor quality teaching or support for their learning. One institutional response

24:02.650 --> 24:07.790
which must be a matter of concern is the upward drift in the UK of the level of passes

24:07.790 --> 24:15.330
and of the grade of degree obtained. Quality assurance systems and the capacity of institutions

24:15.330 --> 24:20.990
in different countries to depend on one another's awards will become steadily more important,

24:21.650 --> 24:27.470
as will the maintenance of employer confidence in awards. At institutional level, robust

24:27.470 --> 24:33.830
and transparent systems of quality assurance, built on peer review and rigorous internal processes,

24:34.410 --> 24:39.550
must be developed to provide the essential protections backed by national and international

24:39.550 --> 24:46.490
systems which verify the integrity of those systems. In the UK the quality assurance agency

24:46.490 --> 24:52.650
fulfils this function. This in turn depends on institutions and academics having the time

24:52.650 --> 24:59.270
and other resources to sustain these quality assurance systems. But contrary to what the

24:59.270 --> 25:04.450
advocates of the market will argue, the philosophy built on the customer relations marketplace

25:04.450 --> 25:11.590
mentality cannot sustain quality in higher education. Bologna can and must play an essential

25:11.590 --> 25:16.870
positive role in insisting that quality assurance mechanisms do their job effectively.

25:18.590 --> 25:23.850
The European Network for Quality Assurance, referred to above, is a European network of public

25:23.850 --> 25:34.210
authorities concerned with quality universities and other institutions. Here, as elsewhere

25:34.210 --> 25:41.410
at European level, intergovernmental and interinstitutional structures marginalise the unions.

25:41.410 --> 25:46.950
The organisations representing the academics were most directly responsible for the maintenance,

25:46.990 --> 25:54.990
delivery and verification of quality. Employer pressure towards decentralised bargaining,

25:55.450 --> 26:00.170
moving away from national or regional or institutional level, and even with the possibility

26:00.170 --> 26:05.790
of individual contracts with staff, all pose a new challenge to our national bargaining systems.

26:06.730 --> 26:11.690
These pressures would place extra burdens on institutions and threaten the fragmentation

26:11.690 --> 26:18.010
of the higher education system itself, making it more opaque to potential students, employers

26:18.010 --> 26:25.870
and other customers, and will accelerate hierarchies of esteem among institutions and foster

26:25.870 --> 26:31.430
inequity and a climate of competition, leading to a pursuit of the lowest common denominator

26:31.430 --> 26:37.470
in salaries and conditions, except, as we've seen in recent years, for football-style

26:38.110 --> 26:44.890
transfer packages to attract academic stars. Equally serious for us in the trade unions,

26:45.390 --> 26:50.750
these trends will cause major organisational and representational problems for the academic

26:50.750 --> 26:55.470
unions as they struggle to deal with more bargaining units and the need for cadres of

26:55.470 --> 27:00.230
dedicated officials or active members to cope with the new bargaining levels.

27:03.270 --> 27:07.370
Until very recently the title and concept of a university was jealously guarded in the

27:07.370 --> 27:13.470
UK, where it required a royal charter to grant the university title. Then in the early

27:13.470 --> 27:18.990
90s the polytechnics as a group became universities by an act of parliament and since then a

27:18.990 --> 27:24.510
number of individual institutions have joined their ranks after meeting prescribed basic

27:24.510 --> 27:29.310
criteria. But the global marketplace wishes to reprocess the image of the university

27:29.310 --> 27:35.070
and see it as a brand which can be attached to forms of provision dissociated from a physical

27:35.070 --> 27:41.470
entity or an institution with any of the characteristics which we would recognise as

27:41.470 --> 27:46.830
defining a university. The University of the Future may well be a website, a network of

27:46.830 --> 27:52.710
electronic resources or an in-house company training programme. Private corporations,

27:52.710 --> 27:57.270
particularly in the USA and in East Asia, are increasingly applying the term university

27:57.270 --> 28:02.950
to their own in-house training operations. One of the UK's largest employers, the National

28:02.950 --> 28:09.150
Health Service, is setting up its own NHS university which will be from the outset one of our

28:09.150 --> 28:14.690
biggest universities, operating through regional consortia with a number of conventional universities

28:14.690 --> 28:21.010
as well as building links to intermediate and school level studies. Such developments

28:21.010 --> 28:25.690
will undoubtedly reach new students or customers in innovative and user-friendly ways.

28:26.190 --> 28:30.950
Their impact on the traditional university and the offers they make remains to be seen.

28:31.530 --> 28:35.990
However, these developments present enormous challenges for staff and their unions and

28:35.990 --> 28:41.270
for the general public in understanding and using such new forms of learning and transmission

28:41.270 --> 28:47.630
of knowledge. The new managerial culture in institutions has already had a significant

28:47.630 --> 28:53.310
effect on institutional culture. It continues to act in a corrosive way, for example,

28:53.590 --> 28:59.590
taking income generation and publishing as key criteria for assessing staff performance.

29:00.550 --> 29:05.110
The fact that this trend has been driven from within the institutions themselves makes obsolete

29:05.110 --> 29:10.850
the belief that institutional autonomy in itself is a protection for academic staff.

29:12.490 --> 29:17.330
It must be noted that some of the trends I have mentioned are common to the schools and

29:17.330 --> 29:22.970
further education sectors too and also that the effects of changes in school education

29:22.970 --> 29:28.270
may compound the problems of higher education. Teachers in higher education need to make

29:28.270 --> 29:32.990
common cause with teachers in other sectors and with administrative and support staff

29:32.990 --> 29:38.430
in universities too. Teachers unions through their international links are ideally placed

29:38.430 --> 29:44.430
to argue the interrelatedness of all sectors of education. Higher education historically has had

29:44.430 --> 29:49.570
and must continue to have a key role in the education of teachers both initially and throughout their

29:49.570 --> 29:55.670
careers. These issues should bind the teachers unions together and enable them to present a

29:55.670 --> 30:01.370
united front at the national level and increasingly at the European and global levels too.

30:02.230 --> 30:06.430
One encouraging trend which I believe is being carried through in Italy too has been the close

30:06.430 --> 30:11.270
working and organisational unity which unions in a number of countries are achieving at the national

30:11.270 --> 30:17.510
level, a trend which is beginning to be felt in the UK in spite of a past fraught with

30:17.510 --> 30:23.430
inter-union rivalries. My own union and our sister union the Association of University Teachers

30:23.430 --> 30:29.710
are now exploring the possibility of amalgamating to form a new single union for post-school teachers.

30:31.990 --> 30:37.990
In UK unions as in other sectors of education creaking structures depend on an ageing cohort

30:37.990 --> 30:44.590
of academic staff in full-time tenured posts able to maintain a balance of teaching, research

30:44.590 --> 30:50.390
and scholarship as well as administrative responsibilities who carry the traditional values of the

30:50.390 --> 30:55.890
university system and who are often the ones challenging threats to those values as individuals

30:55.890 --> 31:01.670
or as union activists. The staff coming after them are often appointed on different

31:35.070 --> 31:43.350
terms while many are on casualised contracts and thus far more vulnerable to the whims of the employer.

31:44.170 --> 31:50.390
The UK unions in higher education also rely heavily on the generation now in its last decade of work

31:50.390 --> 31:56.410
many of whom have faced victimisation or negative effect on their academic careers as consequence

31:56.410 --> 32:02.570
of their union activities. Not only are the younger generation of academics often casualised

32:03.010 --> 32:08.610
part-time or on short-time contracts more difficult to engage in the union as ordinary members

32:08.610 --> 32:14.570
when they look at the way future academic careers are likely to unfold they may take the view that

32:14.570 --> 32:18.930
union activism or even union membership is not good for the health of your career.

32:20.290 --> 32:27.070
This is a major challenge for unions in education. The higher education unions and the UK

32:27.070 --> 32:33.870
trade union congress are urgently seeking to address this issue and to promote a new organising culture

32:33.870 --> 32:40.990
to enable the unions to engage the new generation of workers. All these policies and trends put together

32:40.990 --> 32:46.070
amount to a dramatic and potentially undermining challenge to higher education and research.

32:46.070 --> 32:53.130
The issues raised by Bologna and the global marketplace in higher education run through them as a subtext.

32:54.510 --> 32:59.810
The UK government is complacent about our role in the European and global higher education marketplace

32:59.810 --> 33:07.690
but as so often in the past this complacency may be a misjudgment. Trends which are mostly well under way

33:07.690 --> 33:13.810
in UK universities are often seen as exemplars by some other governments in Europe and elsewhere.

33:13.810 --> 33:20.140
This brings me back to a consideration of the European arena at the midway point between the 2003

33:21.150 --> 33:27.250
Berlin interministerial conference and the Bergen conference in May 2005.

33:30.750 --> 33:38.230
Since the Lisbon declaration of 2000 setting the objective of making the European union the most competitive

33:39.750 --> 33:48.710
and dynamic knowledge based economy in the world, Europe's higher education systems have been put centre stage

33:48.710 --> 33:54.570
in the global economic confrontations that are to come and will be challenged to remodel themselves

33:54.570 --> 34:02.610
to fit this increasingly economy driven role. It is clear that for governments both within the European union

34:02.610 --> 34:08.210
and in the much larger framework of the Bologna process, higher education occupies an important part

34:08.210 --> 34:15.870
on the one hand in building social and economic relations within Europe and on the other in establishing Europe's place

34:15.870 --> 34:25.530
in the global market. Both the EU and the Bologna strands of policy are driving us towards a model which should retain

34:25.530 --> 34:32.190
and may even enhance some of the valued collegial qualities of higher education and research within Europe

34:32.190 --> 34:40.490
in European areas for higher education and for research converging to form the Europe of knowledge.

34:41.130 --> 34:48.570
However, this will be paralleled by a drive to make Europe's higher education system a major player in global economic terms.

34:49.450 --> 34:57.430
We do not yet know whether these two goals are compatible and it seems unlikely unless academics and their unions

34:57.430 --> 35:06.290
are brought more completely within the process. The European Commission on Communication, the role of universities in the Europe of knowledge

35:06.290 --> 35:13.770
published in February 2003 helped shape the discourse in the run up to the Berlin inter-ministerial conference.

35:14.550 --> 35:21.430
While it emphasises the importance of Europe's universities, it offers mainly instrumental economically driven arguments

35:21.430 --> 35:30.530
to the system with the commodification of knowledge and the perceived need to compete with the United States as central strands in its thinking.

35:32.210 --> 35:40.810
The paper is particularly concerned with the gap in terms of scale and the level of resources between the US higher education system

35:40.810 --> 35:46.650
and the European and points to the far higher level of private finance for the US system.

35:47.390 --> 35:56.610
However, the EU paper asked many of the right questions about the future shape of our system, recognising and valuing many of its key characteristics.

35:58.290 --> 36:05.970
The European area for higher education and the European research area are now clearly recognised to be mutually dependent

36:05.970 --> 36:10.010
and must converge and be developed as a single Europe of knowledge.

36:11.010 --> 36:17.550
The European Trade Union Committee for Education, responding to the communication on behalf of the higher education and research unions,

36:18.030 --> 36:27.530
asserted that the diversity of Europe's higher education was a strength that must be retained and challenged the Commission's over-reliance on links with business

36:27.530 --> 36:35.170
as a panacea for questions of funding, institutional management and employability of its students.

36:35.170 --> 36:44.090
It should be noted that these moves are mirrored by the Copenhagen Declaration on Enhanced Cooperation in the Field of Vocational Education

36:44.090 --> 36:51.930
made by 31 European Vocational Education Ministers and the European Commission promulgated in November 2002.

36:53.190 --> 36:56.090
Martin will say more about those trends later.

36:57.230 --> 37:03.110
The European level interest in quality, both at EU level and within the Bologna process,

37:03.550 --> 37:08.430
is driven by a recognition that it is an essential factor in the promotion of mobility

37:09.210 --> 37:17.630
and the more or less common pattern of degrees at Bachelors, Masters and Doctorate level will facilitate this in the long term.

37:18.630 --> 37:26.030
However, it's clear that through the European Network for Quality Assurance and the European Credit Transfer System

37:26.370 --> 37:34.110
and the development of diploma supplements on the initiative of the European Commission, Council of Europe and UNESCO,

37:34.910 --> 37:42.670
the certification of qualifications will need to become more elaborated if it is to make possible the acknowledgement of learning

37:42.670 --> 37:46.510
or meaningful comparisons between students' achievements.

37:48.290 --> 37:55.830
The 2003 Berlin Conference was more concerned with consolidation and exhortation than any new steps,

37:56.270 --> 37:59.990
perhaps recognising that as an ever greater number of countries sign up

37:59.990 --> 38:07.710
and as even the original signatories diverge widely in the way in which and the degree to which they are progressing towards the key objectives,

38:08.290 --> 38:11.530
it was not the moment for further new departures.

38:11.530 --> 38:20.730
It seems, however, that governments and university rectors are willfully ignoring the legitimate voice of higher education teachers and researchers,

38:21.150 --> 38:28.690
arguing either that there is no such concerted voice or that the university rectors are capable of speaking for their staffs.

38:29.770 --> 38:31.570
Neither of these positions is tenable.

38:32.290 --> 38:39.290
The unions representing academic staff have met and collectively voiced their concerns for over 15 years at the European level.

38:39.290 --> 38:48.210
First under the auspices of the ETUCE and more recently within the European Structures of Education International.

38:50.350 --> 38:56.330
Virtually since the beginning of the Bologna process, the higher education unions have been seeking to gain access to the debates

38:56.330 --> 38:58.710
and to broaden the scope of the Bologna agenda.

38:59.450 --> 39:05.190
It was shocking to the millennium that education came closer and closer to the European agenda.

39:05.190 --> 39:08.470
Education became more and more important.

39:09.270 --> 39:18.790
We saw prime ministers, we saw different important people from the private sector also speaking about the importance of education.

39:19.610 --> 39:28.910
It was a real change from the 18th to the 19th that now leading people in society and also private sector were speaking about education.

39:29.010 --> 39:30.210
Why did they do that?

39:30.210 --> 39:35.710
Maybe because they realized that education was in jeopardy in many places.

39:35.870 --> 39:38.150
The quality was down and they needed money.

39:38.930 --> 39:41.810
We could have hoped so, but it was not the reason.

39:41.930 --> 39:43.490
The reason of course was money.

39:44.190 --> 39:53.950
But the reason was that in the 19th, during the 19th, most politicians around the world, especially within the OECD countries,

39:53.950 --> 40:03.470
realized that they had to make a change in policy if they would to sustain with the society in growth,

40:03.810 --> 40:12.710
if they would to have still a welfare society, they would have to put more effort into the quality of education.

40:13.590 --> 40:23.330
So education came into the center of the debate in the European Union in the meeting of the heads of states in Lisbon in 2000.

40:23.330 --> 40:30.670
Because the heads of states, prime ministers and others realized that education was necessary,

40:30.870 --> 40:34.910
that we had to create new parameters for competition.

40:35.990 --> 40:45.870
In the older days when the economy was only based on let's say the parameters of competition that would give an example

40:45.870 --> 40:53.530
and that if you were producing shoes in Italy, then it's about producing so many shoes as possible to the lowest price as possible.

40:54.310 --> 41:00.290
That's true. And if you're good at producing wine in another place also in Italy, then it's about producing...

41:00.290 --> 41:12.350
Then inspired, I think, very much from the Bologna Process, a proposal has now come up for a so-called Common Quality Assurance Framework,

41:12.350 --> 41:19.770
which I guess will more or less follow the discussions that we have seen within the Bologna Process.

41:20.510 --> 41:30.430
Because also here we see an interest not only to streamline the structures but also to set certain parameters for the quality.

41:32.250 --> 41:36.870
Then we have a special situation about the non-formal and informal learning.

41:37.810 --> 41:49.950
The European Council of Ministers have decided the resolution in which they have asked the ministers and the commission

41:49.950 --> 41:58.230
to come up with a proposal for how to make a recognition of the non-formal and informal learning

41:58.230 --> 42:07.930
for many of workers who has been through the education already and actually is in service or at work,

42:08.370 --> 42:18.170
but still have some kind of running education but not always education that are recognized as a formal education.

42:18.170 --> 42:32.550
So a very important part here is also how to make it visible that you are in a lifelong education when you are at work.

42:34.130 --> 42:44.750
Lifelong guidance, still in relation to lifelong learning, I think lifelong learning we could talk lifelong time about that

42:44.750 --> 42:55.350
because it's really one of the huge items in the discussion and something that is on the top agenda

42:55.350 --> 43:07.090
but at the same time something that is completely impossible to implement in the same way in the different member states of the European Union.

43:07.090 --> 43:18.630
It's not really realized by a lot of let's say politicians and maybe also even by some of our trade union fellows

43:18.630 --> 43:28.170
but I think we have to be realistic here and say that there are certain common objectives we can follow about lifelong learning

43:28.170 --> 43:39.530
but when it comes into the implementation of it we have to realize systems are really too different to set up a kind of European lifelong learning system

43:39.530 --> 43:49.010
which many of our colleagues want. I'm sorry but I don't believe in this idea. I think it will be completely impossible.

43:52.390 --> 44:00.950
Then also the possibility of development of qualifications and competences at sector level.

44:01.530 --> 44:12.430
You know there is an advisory body connected with the European Union work on vocational education and training, CITIFOP, with the headquarter in Greece

44:12.430 --> 44:28.370
doing a great work in mapping out the different systems that we have and coming up with different projects and surveys telling about the systems and what could be possible and not possible.

44:28.370 --> 44:47.290
I think that the decision about the Leonardo da Vinci committee, which we also are represented in the ETC, to use a huge lot of money also operating at the sectoral level

44:47.290 --> 44:55.530
can really boost the interest of setting up projects within vocational education and training.

44:55.530 --> 45:18.410
I think that what you are more or less experiencing for the moment in the interest of setting up and driving the Copenhagen process is exactly the same thing that boosted the Lisbon process and are boosting for the moment the Bologna process.

45:18.410 --> 45:28.030
It is a change of society. It is a change of the economy. It is a change of the parameters, the competition parameters I was talking about.

45:28.030 --> 45:48.290
But I think that we have one major interest here also being represented in most of these processes, but for the moment as Paul said, for the moment we are not represented in the Bologna process, but I guess we will be.

45:48.290 --> 46:01.230
I have had some very positive meetings with the Norwegian minister preparing the Bergen meeting in May 2005. I had a positive meeting with the European Dutch presidency.

46:02.390 --> 46:16.310
The minister here were also very positive. The European Commission officially support the ETC to be a member on behalf of our higher education colleagues in the Bologna process.

46:16.310 --> 46:24.790
I am quite confident that this time we will come into the system as official partners.

46:25.350 --> 46:44.070
That of course gives us a kind of obligation to work with the system, but also to put up the views of our academic members and to put up our specific goals for the work that we have as we see the Bologna process.

46:44.070 --> 46:52.350
So it can be quite challenging in 2005 if we get on board the Bologna process formally.

46:53.310 --> 47:04.950
But apart from that, we also need to have a discussion about our approach to education as such in the market economy as Paul said.

47:04.950 --> 47:14.330
It's clear that the interest here in these three processes we have been talking about is boosted by the economic changes.

47:15.030 --> 47:31.370
And when I talk to our dear friends in the European Commission, because they are actually very helpful and somewhat positive and even very constructive when we are working together with education,

47:31.370 --> 47:55.330
it seems though clear to me that a lot of officials and also a lot of government officials from the different member countries think of education like education just being a kind of passive tool for the economy and employment policy.

47:56.910 --> 48:07.830
Just like you go to the cafeteria, you go to the employment cafeteria, you realize you have some problems in society with the structure of the labor market.

48:07.930 --> 48:16.830
You have some employment problems also. So you go into the cafeteria and then you look for the tools to solve those problems.

48:16.830 --> 48:27.030
And one of the tools are marked education and you take it down from the shelf and then you take a little education of this and a little education of that and then you have solved the problem.

48:27.610 --> 48:43.230
I mean, well, that was more or less maybe a joke, but we have to be careful that we defend our, let's say, European, because I actually think we have some here, European values of what education is.

48:43.230 --> 48:59.510
Education is maybe also a tool for economy and employment policy, but education is far more than that. Education is the right for the single person to develop their own personality.

48:59.510 --> 49:13.150
It's about also getting the cultural grasp of society and it's about also developing democracy and it's about grasping the history of the nations in Europe.

49:13.150 --> 49:30.010
I think that we will have as teachers and trade unions the obligation to defend that education is far, far more than a passive tool for the implementation of the economy and employment strategy.

49:30.770 --> 49:39.750
And I think that this is something that we should remember every time when we are discussing this.

49:39.750 --> 49:54.790
I know you this morning said focused also on the new treaty. I also know that in the new treaty there are no changes concerning education when we look to the two articles, the two current articles, 149 and 150.

49:56.130 --> 50:06.970
But there are changes for us as normal citizens and also as public workers. And there are positive and there are negative changes.

50:06.970 --> 50:36.950
We had a big struggle, I will tell you, as ETUC, with the Irish presidency because of the changes that were put in about the public sector, because we more or less felt that the changes that they have put in about the public sector in the treaty would open up for a general approach to education being traded with under normal market circumstances.

50:36.970 --> 50:53.990
And that's because in the current Nice treaty we have paragraph 133 where education is exempted from the normal trade articles and trade rules within the European Union.

50:54.270 --> 50:58.310
But they disappeared with the proposal for the new treaty.

